<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-617-683  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 617 683.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Journal of Object-Oriented Programming  Nov-Dec 1990 v3 n4 p60(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Smalltalk as the first programming language: the Carletonexperience. (Smalltalk) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>LaLonde, Wilf; Pugh, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Carleton University decided to replace Pascal with Smalltalk asits primary programming language.andP;  Smalltalk satisfies theinstructors' goals: support for both data and proceduralabstraction; an advanced environment; interactive tools;implementations running on MS-DOS based microcomputers; simple andminimal syntax; textbooks available; can serve as the linguafranca for the rest of the curriculum; incorporates currentevolution in programming concepts; supports introductory andadvanced courses; and has some industrial relevance.andP;  The seamlessintegration of the Smalltalk language, environment, and classlibrary is what makes the instructors' approach successful; it isalso what makes it a challenge to teach in an appropriate order.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Smalltalk (Computer program language) (Usage).andO;Topic:     TeachingColleges and UniversitiesProgramming LanguagesObject-Oriented ProgrammingCarleton University.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>